<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-291-863  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 291 863.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Jan 30 1989 v6 n4 p47(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Meta debuts graphical program design tool for the Macintosh.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pallatto, John.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Meta Software Corp's Design-ML is a program development tool forcreating graphical software and graphical interfaces.andP;  The programruns on the Apple Macintosh, and may ultimately be ported to thePC.andP;  The tool is written with the Standard ML programming languagefor graphic symbols developed by the University of Edinburgh,Scotland.andP;  The program has the capability of running graphicalexamples of functions without completion of the entire program.andO;The programs prototype design capability can reduce the programdevelopment time by as much as 60 percent, according to companyofficials.andP;  The program sells for $1,000 per copy.andP;  A site licensefor educational institutions is available for the same single-copyprice.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Meta Software Corp. (products).andO;Product:   Design-ml (Program development software).andO;Topic:     Graphics SoftwareProgram Development ToolsInterfaceDesign.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By John PallattoandM;Meta Software Corp. recently introduced a graphical program-design tool forthe Macintosh written in Standard ML, a symbolic programming language.andM;The product, called Design/ML, made its debut at MacWorld earlier this month;its developer hopes to introduce a PC version in the future.andM;Design/ML can be used as an interface-design tool for graphical applicationsfor the Macintosh PC, according to Jawahar Malhotra, the developer of theproduct.andP;  It can also be used as an interactive tool for building programprototypes -- whether the final program will be written in Standard ML orother languages, such as C, LISP or Pascal -- Malhotra said.andM;Standard ML, developed in the 1970s at the University of Edinburgh inScotland, is a symbolic programming language similar to LISP but with commandstructures and functions similar to those found in Pascal.andP;  According toMalhotra, most Pascal programs can be translated into Standard ML with fewchanges.andM;Most ML adherents are computer scientists who are studying symbolicprogramming languages at universities, said Andrew Levin, vice president ofmarketing at Meta Software, in Cambridge, Mass.andM;However, developers in the U.S.andP;  Defense Department and in the business worldare starting to examine the potential of symbolic languages forcommunications, automated manufacturing systems and system simulations, Levinsaid.andM;The graphical capability built into Design/ML and the symbolic processingfunctions of the ML language allow developers to try out various design ideaswithout going through the effort of writing and compiling prototypes in otherlanguages, Malhotra explained.andM;Users who work with Design/ML create diagrams and flow charts that displayboxes and graphics that represent different program functions.andP;  Within eachgraphic is Standard ML code that can be written to represent specific programfunctions.andM;Design/ML gives users access to capabilities built into two other MetaSoftware products: MetaDesign, a program diagram-and flowchart-developmentpackage; and Design/OA, a development system for object-oriented graphicsapplications.andM;The prototype-design capability of Design/ML can reduce the amount of time itwould take to develop a prototype application on a Macintosh by 40 percent to60 percent, according Levin.andM;Design/ML runs on Mac Plus, SE and Mac II machines.andP;  Meta is also makingplans to offer a version of Design/ML that will let the ML compiler run onnetworked Sun Microsystems Inc. workstations connected to Macs providing theuser interface.andM;Design/ML is being offered for $1,000 per copy.andP;  Meta Software is offering asite license to educational institutions for the $1,000 single-copy price,Levin said.andP;  Meta Software can be contacted at (617) 576-6920.andO;</TEXT></DOC>